To specify the LED to be toggled, you will typically need to provide the name or pin number of the LED in your code or circuit design. Depending on the platform or device you are working with, there may be different ways of doing this.

For example, if you are working with an Arduino board, you can use the `digitalWrite()` function to specify the LED pin and toggle its state. The parameter you pass to this function will need to correspond to the pin number where the LED is connected.

Assuming you have connected an LED to pin 13 of your Arduino board, you could toggle it on and off by writing the following code:

```
void setup() {
  pinMode(13, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  digitalWrite(13, HIGH);
  delay(1000);
  digitalWrite(13, LOW);
  delay(1000);
}
```

In this code, `pinMode(13, OUTPUT)` sets the mode of pin 13 to output, indicating that it will be used to toggle the LED. Then, in the `loop()` function, `digitalWrite(13, HIGH)` sets the LED pin to HIGH, turning it on, and `digitalWrite(13, LOW)` sets it to LOW, turning it off. The `delay()` function adds a delay of 1000 milliseconds (1 second) between each state change, giving the effect of the LED blinking on and off.

This is just an example, and the syntax and methodology will vary depending on the platform or device you are working with.
